text.Taxonomy and naming:
Eucalyptus insularis was first formally described in 1974 by Ian Brooker from a specimen collected on North Twin Peak Island in the Recherche Archipelago and the description was published in the journal Nuytsia. The specific epithet (insularis) is a Latin word meaning 'of an island', referring to the location of the type specimen.In 2014, Dean Nicolle and Ian Brooker described to subspecies of E. insularis and the names have been accepted by the Australian Plant Census:
Eucalyptus insularis subsp. continentalis D.Nicolle & Brooker a spreading malle with adult leaves 3–6 mm (0.12–0.24 in) wide;
Eucalyptus insularis Brooker subsp. insularis an erect, multi-stemmed malle with leaves 6–9 mm (0.24–0.35 in) wide.
